%N A393193 a(n) is the integer angle bisector of the triangle (A394102(n), A394101(n), A394100(n)).
%H A393193 Felix Huber, <a href="/A393193/b393193.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A393193 a(1) = 4 since the triangle (A394102(1), A394101(1), A394100(1)) = (5, 5, 6) has the internal bisector l_z = 4 that splits y = 6 into 3 and 3, yielding two congruent triangles (3, 4, 5), and gcd(5, 5, 6, 4) = 1.
%e A393193 a(6) = 10 since the triangle (A394102(6), A394101(6), A394100(6)) = (12, 15, 18) has the internal bisector l_y = 10 that splits y = 15 into 6 and 9, yielding triangles (6, 10, 12) and (9, 10, 18), and gcd(12, 15, 18, 10) = 1.
